{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_dill_ver02/data/sn91068695/00279559447/1945101101/0332.xml":{"full_text":"THE MARION PROGRESS\nPUBLISHED EVERY THURSDAY BY THE\nMcdowell publishing co.\nMARION, N. C.\nTELEPHONE 64\nS. E. WHITTEN, Editor arid Proprietor\nEntered at the Postoffice at Marion, N. C.,\nas second class matter.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATE:\nOne Year $1.50\nStrictly in Advance.\nWHY OUR HELP IS VITAL\nTho need of the National War Fund for fin\nances is actually greater than ever this year, j\nThere are vast troop movements over thousands j\nof miles. Help and entertainment must be car- j\nried farther than ever, and these men and wo-1\nmen need more than food, and a place to sleep,\nto enable them to withstand the hardships, the j\nloneliness, and the horrors of war.\nThe things they receive through the U. S. O.,\nUnited Seamen's Service, and War Prisoner's j\nAid, and things that help sustain them j\nthings that let them know the people of this i\ncountry are \"in there with them.\" Things that j\ntell them they do not fight alone.\nThe need for aid in liberated countries is J\npressing acute. This is going to be a fat- j\nal year for millions of men, women and child-1\nren if we do not help them. We can't let I\nthem down now.\nIn addition, the need here at home in our\nown communities has been increased by four\nyears of war. This year, the funds collected j\nmust do more than ever.\nThe goal for McDowell county is $9,950. The j\ndrive to raise this amount started this week.\nEvery citizen is urged to give generously to this\nfund.\nPLEASURE OR DUTY? 'j\nCourtesy in business relations may be a duty\nor a pleasure. It has been so long overlooked j\nthat it is easy to forget there is genuine plea- J\nsure in giving as well as receiving cordial words\nand needs.\nWe quote an editorial from Christian Science\nMonitor illustrating this point and entitled,\n\"People\": s\n\"The conductor climbed aboard with his j\nhandful of roses. Every morning that summer j\nwhen the train stopped at the station below the j\nrose bank\u2014the running kin they plant to hold\nthe soil\u2014he had picked his bouquet in the min- j\nlite it took for the commuters to file into the\nI\ncoaches. Then he would swing on the step as\nthe train moved out, his bright blue eyes twinkl\ning beneath bushy white eyebrows and the\nblack beak of his cap.\n\"Every morning a half dozen or more of the\nlady passengers were favored with a rose, a\nsmile and a bow. This morning the one junior\nmiss who rode the forward coach was fast\nasleep, curled up against the window. The\nconductor stopped, gently wove a rose stem\ninto her hair, smiled benighnly to the car in\ngeneral and walked on down the aisle.\"\nFIRE PREVENTION IS YOUR JOB\nAs tne mon on the street watches the fire en\ngine roar by with the siren going, he is more\napt to get a thrill than a chill from wondering\nwhether it is his home or the place of business\nhe works that may be on fire. Every.,day count\nless people have to hunt new homes or new\nplaces to work because they were \"burned\nout.\"\nAt this particular time, when reconversion is\njust getting underway, a fire can be particul\narly disastrous to employment, for two reasons:\nPlans are still hard to replace; and with much\nuncertainty about the use of surplus govern\nment properties, there may be justified hesi\ntancy about rebuilding. So anything that can\nbe done to avert fire, helps prevent unneces\nsary unemployment or moving, with resultant\nloss of earnings or savings.\nnre prevention is a nigniy personal proDiem\nwhich can save more than fire fighting. Ev\nery man or woman who lights a match or\nsmokes a cigarette should strive to be conscious\nof the fact that such articles are extinguished\nbefore they leave their fingers. Every person\nusing heat-producing electric, should be sure\nit is out before leaving it. Every person tend\ning a furnace or a stove, or handling gasoline or\nany other inflammable material, should be con\nstantly alert to the danger of fire, and cause\neach of their acts to be one of fire prevention,\ninstead of fire carelessness.\nIf individuals would make themselves re\nsponsible for fire prevention, much loss and\nsuffering could be averted during the recon\nversion period, which no fire department or no\nfire insurance company can eliminate.\nDon't forget that the war will not be over,\nso far as the United States is concerned, until\nall our veteran soldiers and sailors have been\nbrought home.\nThe time to begin to be financially independ\nent is now; spend less than you make is the\nonly rule.\nThe best way to welcome returning veterans\nis to see that they have what some people term\nan economic opportunity.\nWe have never been able to understand why\nthose who need no vation always manage to\nget one.\nSALVAGING OF FATS\nSTILL MUCH NEEDED\nThe fat situation is still acute, be\ncause it is unlikely that any apprec\niable supply of oils will be received\nfrom the areas surrendered by the\nJapanese for some time to come,\nsays Mrs. Estelle T. Smith of State\nCollege, chairman of the N. C. Fat\nSalvage Committee.\nSalvaged fats,' so important in\nthe war program, are today a No. 1\nitem in the reconversion plan. Mrs.\nI Smith urges that there be no' let\ndown in the drive for maximum\nused-fat collections.\nShe asks that the more than forty\n(thousand home demonstration club\nwomen and all of the boys and girls\nin the 4-H clubs throughout the\nstate continue their activities in sav\nI\ning, collecting, and delivering used\nfats to concentration points in local\nareas.\n\"Agricultural workers councils\nand groups of neighborhood leaders\nin- rural areas, both men and wom\nen, can be of great service to their\ncountry and materially help in\nspeeding the reconversion program\nby consistently working for the col\nlection of used fats,\" Mrs. Smith de\nclares. \"While there has been an\nMAN HAD BRICK IN HIS\nSTOMACH FOR 10 YEARS\nOne man recently stated that for\n10 years he felt like he had a brick\nin his stomach. This feeling was\ndue to the lump of undigested food\nhe always had inside of him. He\nwas weak, worn out, headachy,\nswollen with gas and terribly con\nstipated. Recently he started tak\ning INNER-AID and says the feel\ning like a brick in his stomach\ndisappeared the second day. Bowels\nare regular now, gas and headaches\nare gone and he feels like a new\nman.\nINNER-AID contains 12 Great\nHerbs; they cleanse bowels, clear\ngas from stomach, act on sluggish\nliver and kidneys. Miserable peo\nple soon feel different all over. So\ndon't go on suffering! Get INNER\nAID4. Sold by all Drug Stores here\nin McDowell County.\n6 6 6\nCold Preparations\nLiquid, Tablets, Salve, Nose Drops\nUse Only As Directed\nd. FALSE TEETH\nRock, Slide or Slip?\nFASTEETH, an improved powder to\nbe sprinkled on upper or lower plates,\nholds false teeth more firmly in place.\nDo not slide, slip or rock. No gummy,\nKooey, pasty taste or feeling. PAS\nTEETH is alkaline (non-acid). Does not\nsour. Checks \"plate odor\" (denture\nbreath). Get FASTEETH at any drug\nstore.\nincrease in the quarterly quota of j\nfats and oils for the production of\ncivilian supplies of soap, still the sit- i\nuation on oils continues to remain\nacute and the need for the salvag-j\ning of fats in the home is one of the\nmost important points in the recon-1\nversion plan.\" i\nPOISON IVY\nHOW TO KILL IT\nKill the outer skin. It peels oft\nand with it goes the ivy infection.\nOften one application is enough. Get\nTe-ol solution at any drug- store.\nIt's powerful. Stops itching quickly.\nYour 35c back tomorrow it not\npleased. Today at\nStreetman's.\n(INCORPORATED)\n\u2014PRESENTS\u2014\nUP TO THE MINUTE\nRiding\nDevices\nUNDER THE AUSPICES OF THE McDOWElX\nPOST OF THE AMERICAN LEGION\nIN MARION\nDURING WEEK OF\nOctober 15\nthrough 20\nON LOT ON CORNER WEST HENDERSON\nDEPOT STREETS\nThe Everyday\nCounselor\nBy Rev, Herbert Spaugh, D. D.\nThe Murder Factory is back in j\nbusiness again and the Butcher j\nWagon is rolling! Since the aboli-;\ntion of gasoline rationing auto traf- j\nfic accidents and deaths have reach- j\ned a new high. Lest we take vigor-1\ncus preventive steps, the rate will\ngo higher. Many old cars are on\n\u25a0the road with unsafe tires. Inex-!\nperienced drivers are at the wheels\nof many of these cars. Our schools\nhave opened again, turning loose a\nflood of children on the streets and\nhighways.\nGasoline rationing put a brake on\na 11 of this, and our traffic accidents\ndropped off. Now the brake is off\nas applied by the government, and\nunless we apply it ourselves there\nwill be many new graves in ceme\nteries and a whole army of new\ncripples not made on the battle\nfields. All this brings vividly back\n\u25a0to my mind an article in the Read\ner's Digest of April, 1938, \"Crip\npled,\" written by a mother in a hos\npital room where her little John\nPaul lies whimpering, \"Mummy, I\nwant to get up. Please, Mummy!\"\nThe mother tells herself that four\nyear-old John Paul wlil never get\nup again \"That is, never as a\nwhole, free, exultant little boy.\"\nIt was because of \"what a boy in\none instance did because he was late\nfor his date with a girl.\" To the\npolice he said, \"I was going fifty\u2014\nlate for a date.\"\nThe mother concludes, \"I am not\nwriting just as John Paul's mother;\nI'm writing for all people who have\nhad to suffer for this irresponsible j\ncrippling of some one dear to them*\nwho have had to rebuild lives as I\nshall have to.\n\"Is there no one to speak for the\n50,000 crippled each year by some- i\none's negligence? (The present\nrate is higher than that), Is there I\nno way of arousing the conscience\nof the drivers of this nation? It is\ntoo late for my John Paul, but not\nfor other childhood, as yet whole,\nable, free.\"\nThis is an appeal to parents:\nPLEASE, 0 PLEASE, TEACH\nYOUR SON AND DAUGHTER TO\nDRIVE THAT CAR BEFORE YOU\nTURN HIM LOOSE WITH IT. Give\nthem all the driving experience you\ncan while you are with them in the\ncar. Be sure that your car is mech\nI anically safe before you give it to\njthem to drive. Take them to your\npolice department and let them see j\nI the pictures there of the Victims of\ninegligent drivers. Your police will\nbe glad to cooperate. Teach your\ni small children to be careful and to\nwatch where they walk or ride their\nbicycles. Life insurance compan\nies are publishing little story books\nto help you with this. Ask your life\ninsurance agent.\nThis is an appeal to our young\npeople among whom statistics show\nthere is the highest rate of acci\ndents: Please, 0 please, be careful\nwith your driving. That automobile\nlis a deadly weapon. You can never\nbring back a life snuffed out by your\ncarelessness, and you will never,\nnever forget it.\nTime for a get-together... Have a Coke\n...or making the party a success\nIt's easy to plan a date at home when you have frosty bottles of Coca-Cola ii$ the\nfamily refrigerator. Have a Co\\e says the hostess, and the affair is off to a flying start.\nTo young or old, this friendly invitation opens the Way to better acquaintance, adds\nzest and enjoyment to entertaining. From Alabama to Oregon, Coca-Cola stands for\nthe pause that refreshes\u2014a pleasant way to make folks feel at home.\nBOTTIED UNDER AUTHORITY OF THE COCA-COLA COMPANY BY\nCoca-Cola Bottling Company, Marion, N. C.\nCoke Coca-Cola\ni \"Coca-Cola\" and its abbreviation\n\"Coke\" are the registered trade\ni marks which distinguish the prod\nI uct of The Coca-Cola Company.\n1945 Th\u00ae C-C Co..\nUse the Want Ads for profit. Advs. get attention, and results. MARION PROGRESS\u2014Newspaper and Job Printing","height":"31572","width":"21336"}}
